    id: "p-rmc2-01",
    title: "The Honest Liar: Forgery and the Cult of Authenticity",
    text: "When the forger Han van Meegeren confessed, in 1945, that the 'Vermeer' for which a Dutch court was about to try him had been painted not in Delft in the 1660s but in his own studio a few years earlier, the painting did not change. Not one molecule of pigment rearranged itself. Yet overnight it travelled from masterpiece to embarrassment, from national treasure to evidence. Museums that had wept over it now declined to hang it. The lesson is usually taken to be that forgery is a crime against art; I have come to suspect it is better read as an experiment performed upon us, and that the results are not flattering.\n\nConsider what, precisely, was lost when the attribution collapsed. The composition remained; the brushwork remained; whatever capacity the canvas had to arrest the eye on a Tuesday afternoon remained. What vanished was a story — the story of a particular seventeenth-century hand — and with it the peculiar thrill of proximity to genius. It turns out that a great deal of what we call aesthetic experience is in fact biographical tourism. We do not so much look at paintings as visit them, the way one visits a grave, and the forger's crime is less deception than trespass: he has been found squatting in a shrine.\n\nThe standard defence of our outrage is that a forgery genuinely tells us less. An authentic Vermeer is evidence of what one mind, in one century, could do; a fake is evidence only of what a later mind could counterfeit. This is true, and it is not nothing. But notice how far it shifts the ground: the argument now values the painting as a document rather than as an object of delight, and documents are the business of historians, not of the ecstatic crowds queuing round the block. If we were candid, museum labels would read 'important evidence' rather than 'sublime achievement', and the queues, I suspect, would thin.\n\nThe art market, meanwhile, has quietly converted authenticity from a fact into a commodity, and commodities require scarcity. Hence the machinery of certification — the connoisseur's eye, the catalogue raisonné, the laboratory with its infrared and its isotopes — all of it dedicated to manufacturing the one thing the forger cannot copy: a pedigree. There is an irony here that the market prefers not to examine. The more sophisticated our tests become, the more we concede that the eye alone cannot tell the real from the false; and if the eye cannot tell, then whatever the eye receives — the beauty, in short — is demonstrably present in both objects. We pay the premium precisely for what we cannot see.\n\nNone of this quite persuades me to take the forger's side, though several critics, enjoying the frisson of paradox, have done so, hailing him as the great debunker of bourgeois fetishism. That seems to me too easy. The forger does not want to debunk the cult of authenticity; he wants to tax it. His entire livelihood depends on the superstition he is supposed to be exploding — a Vermeer forger in a world genuinely indifferent to attribution would starve. He is less a heretic than a corrupt priest, selling counterfeit relics to a congregation whose faith he requires intact.\n\nAnd yet the experiment stands, and its findings deserve more honesty than we usually give them. We say we love art for itself, and the forger demonstrates, with laboratory rigour, that we love it for its provenance. Perhaps the mature response is neither to renounce the love of provenance nor to pretend it is something else, but to admit that art answers two appetites at once: the appetite of the eye, which the forger can feed, and the appetite for communion with the dead, which he can only counterfeit. The first is aesthetic; the second is closer to religion. Our mistake — the mistake van Meegeren monetised — is our insistence on calling both of them by the same name.",
