    title: "Standing on Ceremony: The Rhetoric of Scientific Modesty",
    text: "Isaac Newton's remark that he had seen further only 'by standing on the shoulders of giants' is routinely quoted as the gold standard of scientific humility, usually by people unaware that he deployed it in a letter to Robert Hooke — a short man with a crooked back, and Newton's bitterest rival — where its generosity has always struck some readers as a stiletto in ceremonial wrapping. Whether or not the barb was intended, the episode makes a serviceable emblem for my subject, which is not the humility of scientists but their rhetoric of humility: a genre with its own conventions, its own occasions, and its own quietly immodest uses.\n\nThe conventions are learned early and observed with liturgical care. The discovery is always announced as a 'contribution'; the decades of obsession are recast as luck ('we were fortunate in our choice of problem'); the paper's final sentence performs the ritual genuflection, 'much work remains to be done'. Nobel lectures are a connoisseur's archive of the form: the laureate ascribes everything to mentors, students, funding bodies and fortune, in inverse proportion to the audience's certainty that ambition of a rather ferocious kind was involved throughout. None of this is dishonest, exactly. It is politeness raised to the level of epistemology — and, like most politeness, it is doing harder work than it admits.\n\nPart of that work is internal discipline. The community's founding anxiety is the corrupting effect of personality on evidence, and the modesty ritual is its standing inoculation: by ceremonially deleting the self from the account ('it was observed that...'), the scientist rehearses the ideal that nature, not reputation, should settle disputes. One need not believe the deletion is real — laboratories seethe with vanity, as their memoirs cheerfully attest — to see that the pretence is functional. A community that obliges its members to speak as though they were replaceable is thereby reminding them that, evidentially speaking, they had better be: a result that only its discoverer can obtain is not a result but an anecdote.\n\nBut the same rhetoric has a public face, and there its workings are more ambiguous. 'We could be wrong' is, within the seminar room, a methodological reflex. Broadcast to a lay audience, it undergoes a strange inversion: the confession of fallibility becomes a credential, the very mark that distinguishes the scientist from the charlatan, whose defining feature is that he is never in doubt. Modesty, in other words, has become the profession's most persuasive form of advertising — and the professionals know it. When a public-health official says 'the evidence is still emerging', she is simultaneously reporting a fact and performing a trustworthiness that no amount of asserted certainty could buy. The performance is sincere; it is also, unavoidably, a performance.\n\nThe trouble arrives when audiences take the ritual literally in one direction but not the other. The same public that hears confident charlatans as strong and hedging scientists as weak has been taught, by the scientists themselves, that hedging is what honesty sounds like — yet in a crisis it reliably rewards the wrong voice. Worse, the modesty script can be weaponised by its enemies: 'even the scientists admit they don't know' is the tribute that motivated doubt pays to methodological candour. Some researchers have drawn the obvious conclusion and coarsened their public speech into slogans, reasoning that a simplified truth outcompetes an honest hedge. I understand the temptation and think it a slow-acting poison: the authority being spent in those slogans was accumulated, over centuries, precisely by the refusal to speak that way.\n\nSo I end in defence of the ritual, provided we see it clearly. Scientific modesty is not a window into scientific souls, which are as various and as vain as anyone's. It is a uniform — and the argument for uniforms was never that soldiers are identical, but that the office should outrank the man. When a scientist says 'much work remains to be done', she is not describing her feelings. She is keeping a promise the profession made long before her birth: that its claims would always arrive dressed for correction. The day that promise is dropped in favour of sounding certain, science will not have become more honest. It will merely have become one more voice in the shouting, with better instruments.",
