    title: "Solvitur Ambulando: Walking as Thinking",
    text: "The Latin tag solvitur ambulando — 'it is solved by walking' — is first recorded as a philosopher's joke: confronted with Zeno's proof that motion is impossible, Diogenes the Cynic is said to have stood up and walked across the room. The anecdote is usually retold as a triumph of common sense over sophistry, which rather misses its bite. Diogenes was not refuting the argument; no argument was offered. He was demonstrating that some problems are not to be answered but outwalked — that the body, put in motion, can simply decline the terms on which a difficulty has been posed. Every genuine thinking-walk since has been a footnote to that gesture.\n\nThe association between walking and thought is so well attested as to be a cliché — Rousseau claiming his mind worked only with his legs, Kierkegaard walking Copenhagen into paragraphs, the Kantian citizens of Königsberg setting their watches by the philosopher's constitutional — and like most clichés it is defended with explanations that arrive suspiciously after the fact. The current favourites are physiological: mild exertion bathes the brain in blood and favourable chemistry, and the science, as far as it goes, is not in dispute. But the explanation explains too little. Cycling irrigates the cortex just as generously, yet no one proposes solvitur pedalando; the treadmill supplies identical exertion and is, on the evidence of every gym in the world, where thoughts go to die. If walking thinks, it is not only because the heart beats faster.\n\nWhat the treadmill lacks — and what I take to be the active ingredient — is passing scenery that asks nothing of us. Walking occupies the mind's restless outer office with a stream of trivial, effortless novelty: a gate, a dog, a smell of rain on dust. So employed, the doorkeeper of consciousness stops vetting the traffic within, and the interior conversation is left profitably unsupervised. This is why the walker's best ideas so seldom concern what is actually before his eyes, and why the phrase 'lost in thought' names, with unintended precision, a navigational condition. It is also why the practice fails the moment it becomes purposeful. Set out to solve the problem and you have brought the office with you; the walk has become a meeting. The gift arrives only when it is not applied for — a rule, as every insomniac and every artist knows, that governs a whole family of goods.\n\nNotice, too, that the pace of walking is the pace of syntax. A sentence, like a path, is a linear affair that must be taken in order, one foot after another, with subordinate clauses as detours that promise to rejoin the main way. I do not think it accidental that the age of the great walkers was also the age of the great sentences, or that thought composed at three miles an hour tends to come back articulated, while insights received in cars arrive as slogans — flashes with no route attached. The walker does not merely have thoughts; he has them in sequence, and sequence is nine-tenths of sense.\n\nIt would be dishonest to leave the subject without conceding how much borrowed grandeur clings to it. Walking has been so thoroughly canonised — by Romantic poets, by essayists rich in leisure, latterly by the publishing category one bookseller of my acquaintance calls 'men looking at hills' — that a suspicion of self-congratulation attends the whole business. The pedestrian literature seldom mentions those for whom walking is not epiphany but transport of last resort; the commuter trudging the hard shoulder past broken-down buses is unlikely to be gathering material for an essay. To walk for thought is a luxury exactly as large as the option of not walking. That the luxury is cheap does not make it universal.\n\nAnd still the old tag holds, if we read it modestly. Walking will not solve what is genuinely hard about a hard problem; Zeno's paradox survived Diogenes' stroll and kept mathematicians employed for two millennia. What the walk dissolves is not the problem but the knot in the person holding it — the clench of attention that mistakes grip for progress. You return with the difficulty intact and yourself rearranged, which turns out, surprisingly often, to have been the difficulty. Solvitur ambulando: not everything, and not for everyone. But the walker returns rearranged, and the rearranged, as often as not, no longer need the solution they set out for.",
